<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRI Council Appoints New Secretary General </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRI Council Appoints New Secretary General </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1505201094 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 14 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1505201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "ACIR Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Ignacio Pichardo Pagaza has been appointed the 
Institutional Revolutionary Party's [PRI] secretary general by 
the PRI's National Political Council. 
  Ignacio Pichardo Pagaza was born in Toluca, Mexico State, on 
13 November 1935. He is the son of Attorney Carlos Pichardo 
Cruz and Maria del Carmen Pagaza Varela. He is married to 
Julieta Lechuga, who is a voluntary social worker. 
  In 1953 Pichardo Pagaza enrolled in National Autonomous 
University of Mexico's Law School, where he earned a bachelor's 
degree in law and graduated in 1958 with a thesis entitled "The 
Judicial Basis of Economic Planning in Mexico." 
  He earned a bachelor's degree in industrial relations and a 
master's degree in administration and public finances at the 
London School of Economics, UK, and another master's in 
administration at Dartmouth College in the United States. 
  Regarding his political activities, which is what interests 
us, Pichardo Pagaza has worked as IEPES [Institute for 
Political, Economic, and Social Studies] coordinator. He also 
was a member of the PRI's CEN [Central Executive Committee] and 
a consultant to the CNC [National Peasant Confederation]. 
  Pichardo Pagaza served as a federal deputy for Toluca and 
was 
president of the Programming and Public Budget Commission. He 
was also Government Secretariat general secretary and Finance 
and Public Credit Secretariat income under secretary. 
  As an academic, Ignacio Pichardo was a professor at the 
Mexico School and author of works such as "Ten Years of Planning 
and Public Administration" and "Our Nation's Fiscal Policy." He 
also published the books: "Public Administration and Urban 
Development" and "The Mexican State's Municipal Development 
Institute in Mexican Productivity and Public Administration." 
  Pichardo Pagazo served as ambassador to Spain until 5 April 
[date as heard], when he was appointed PRI CEN secretary general. 

</TEXT>

